"Novakov T., Menon S., Kirchstetter T.W., Koch D., Hansen J.E.","Aerosol organic carbon to black carbon ratios: Analysis of published data and implications for climate forcing",2005,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","110","21", D21205,"1","12",,,10.1029/2005JD005977,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-29244457274&partnerID=40&md5=543b7cb96e8e63d432dd3ab4ac77ad85","Environmental Energy Technologies Division, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Centre for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Columbia University, Earth Institute, New York, NY 10025, United States","Novakov, T., Environmental Energy Technologies Division, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Menon, S., Environmental Energy Technologies Division, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Kirchstetter, T.W., Environmental Energy Technologies Division, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Koch, D., Centre for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Hansen, J.E., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Columbia University, Earth Institute, New York, NY 10025, United States","Measurements of organic carbon (OC) and black carbon (BC) concentrations over a variety of locations worldwide have been analyzed to infer the spatial distributions of the ratios of OC to BC. Since these ratios determine the relative amounts of scattering and absorption, they are often used to estimate the radiative forcing due to aerosols. An artifact in the protocol for filter measurements of OC has led to widespread overestimates of the ratio of OC to BC in atmospheric aerosols. We developed a criterion to correct for this artifact and analyze corrected OC to BC ratios. The OC to BC ratios, ranging from 1.3 to 2.4, appear relatively constant and are generally unaffected by seasonality, sources, or technology changes, at the locations considered here. The ratios compare well with emission inventories over Europe and China but are a factor of 2 lower in other regions. The reduced estimate for OC/BC in aerosols strengthens the argument that reduction of soot emissions maybe a useful approach to slow global warming. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"aerosol; climate forcing; organic carbon",,,,,,"Bond, T.C., Street, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S.M., Woo, J.-H., Klimont, Z., A technology-based global inventory of black and organic carbon emissions from combustion (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. D14203. , doi:10.1029/2003JD003697; Cachier, H., Brémond, M.P., Buat-Ménard, P., Thermal separation of soot carbon (1989) Aerosol Sci. Technol., 10, pp. 358-364; Cadle, S.H., Dasch, J.M., Wintertime concentrations and sinks of atmospheric particulate carbon at a rural location in northern Michigan (1988) Atmos. Environ., 22, pp. 1373-1381; Cao, J.J., Lee, S.C., Ho, K.F., Zhang, X.Y., Zou, S.C., Fung, K., Chow, J.C., Watson, J.G., Characteristics of carbonaceous aerosol in Pearl River Delta Region, China during 2001 winter period (2003) Atmos. Environ., 37, pp. 1451-1460; Carvalho, A., Pio, C., Santos, C., Water-soluble hydroxylated organic compounds in German and Finnish aerosols (2003) Atmos. Environ., 37, pp. 1775-1783; Castro, L.M., Pio, C.A., Harrison, R.M., Smith, D.J.T., Carbonaceous aerosols in urban and rural European atmospheres: Estimation of secondary organic carbon concentrations (1999) Atmos. Environ., 31, pp. 2771-2781; Chen, L.-W.A., Doddridge, B.G., Dickerson, R.R., Chow, J.C., Henry, R.C., Origins of fine aerosol mass in the Baltimore-Washington corridor: Implications from observation, factor analysis, and ensemble air parcel back trajectories (2002) Atmos. Environ., 36, pp. 4541-4554; Chow, J.C., Watson, J.G., Pritchett, L.C., Pierson, W.R., Frazier, C.A., Purcell, R.G., Th